1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,750
If you've ever had to manage a live conference —

2
00:00:09,050 --> 00:00:12,050
keeping track of which speaker is on stage,

3
00:00:12,350 --> 00:00:16,100
whether they're running late, what the AV team is doing,

4
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:18,650
what the interpreter room needs —

5
00:00:18,950 --> 00:00:21,575
you know how chaotic it can get.

6
00:00:21,875 --> 00:00:26,000
CueDeck is a realtime production console built specifically for live events.

7
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:28,925
One URL, every role, everything synced instantly.

8
00:00:29,225 --> 00:00:32,225
Let me show you what it can do.

9
00:00:32,525 --> 00:00:35,150
CueDeck lives entirely in the browser —

10
00:00:35,450 --> 00:00:39,575
no app to install, no setup wizard that takes three hours.

11
00:00:39,875 --> 00:00:43,250
You sign in, pick your event, and you're in.

12
00:00:43,550 --> 00:00:46,925
What you see here is the Production Console —

13
00:00:47,225 --> 00:00:49,225
this is the director view.

14
00:00:49,525 --> 00:00:54,025
On the left you've got a live session list for today's event.

15
00:00:54,325 --> 00:00:56,575
Each card shows the session title,

16
00:00:56,875 --> 00:00:59,500
the room, the speaker, the planned time,

17
00:00:59,800 --> 00:01:01,800
and the current status.

18
00:01:02,100 --> 00:01:05,100
On the right is the context panel —

19
00:01:05,400 --> 00:01:07,650
this is where you take action.

20
00:01:07,950 --> 00:01:10,575
Go live, put a session on hold,

21
00:01:10,875 --> 00:01:13,875
call the speaker to stage, apply a delay.

22
00:01:14,175 --> 00:01:16,425
Every action is a single click,

23
00:01:16,725 --> 00:01:20,850
and it propagates to every connected device in under a second.

24
00:01:21,150 --> 00:01:24,900
CueDeck has six roles, each with exactly the right level

25
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:27,200
of access for the job.

26
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:29,750
The Director has full control —

27
00:01:30,050 --> 00:01:32,050
they see everything, do everything.

28
00:01:32,350 --> 00:01:35,725
Stage managers can transition sessions and mark speaker arrivals.

29
00:01:36,025 --> 00:01:39,025
AV can see what's live and what's coming.

30
00:01:39,325 --> 00:01:43,075
Interpretation rooms get a dedicated view with the session queue.

31
00:01:43,375 --> 00:01:45,625
Registration sees who's next on stage.

32
00:01:45,925 --> 00:01:50,050
And the Signage role manages the digital displays around the venue.

33
00:01:50,350 --> 00:01:54,100
Everyone gets the right information at the right time —

34
00:01:54,400 --> 00:01:57,400
no more group chats, no more walkie-talkie chaos.

35
00:01:57,700 --> 00:02:01,450
Over the next episodes we're going to walk through every

36
00:02:01,750 --> 00:02:04,375
feature — live, in a real event.

37
00:02:04,675 --> 00:02:06,925
We'll create an event from scratch,

38
00:02:07,225 --> 00:02:10,975
add sessions, run them through the full state machine —

39
00:02:11,275 --> 00:02:13,275
READY, LIVE, HOLD, ENDED.

40
00:02:13,575 --> 00:02:16,575
You'll see the delay cascade, the broadcast bar,

41
00:02:16,875 --> 00:02:19,875
the digital signage system with ten display modes,

42
00:02:20,175 --> 00:02:22,425
the AI agents that help when

43
00:02:22,725 --> 00:02:25,350
things go sideways, the stage confidence monitor,

44
00:02:25,650 --> 00:02:28,275
the stage timer, and a lot more.

45
00:02:28,575 --> 00:02:32,325
By the end of this series you'll be able to

46
00:02:32,625 --> 00:02:35,625
run your first production event on CueDeck solo.

47
00:02:35,925 --> 00:02:39,675
CueDeck is free to try — no credit card needed.

48
00:02:39,975 --> 00:02:42,225
Head to app.cuedeck.io, create your account,

49
00:02:42,525 --> 00:02:45,525
and follow along with the next episode where

50
00:02:45,825 --> 00:02:48,450
we'll set up our first event together.

51
00:02:48,750 --> 00:02:52,125
If you've got questions drop them in the comments.

52
00:02:52,425 --> 00:02:54,675
I'll see you in episode two.
